  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThis article argues that self-hosted Docker users bear full security responsibility, offering practical strategies to mitigate risks from unpatched services, misconfigurations, and exposed secrets. Key topics include version pinning over `:latest`, secure secret management (e.g., avoiding `.env` files), network segmentation, and runtime validation tools like canary tokens. Targeted at home and cloud self-hosters, the tutorial-style guide blends code examples (e.g., Nginx auth proxy setup) with metaphors like \"keeping out the riff-raff\" to frame security as a proactive, hands-on endeavor. It emphasizes balancing effort and security, from hobbyist setups to production-grade hardening.",
